A Clockwork Orange

A Clockwork Orange (1971) is a dystopian crime film adapted, produced, and directed by Stanley Kubrick, based on Anthony Burgess's 1962 novel of the same name. It employs disturbing, violent images to comment on psychiatry, juvenile delinquency, youth gangs, and other social, political, and economic issues in a dystopian near-future Britain.

 

Released in late 1971, the film sparked considerable controversy in the U.S. with its X-rated violence; after copycat crimes in England, Kubrick withdrew the film from British distribution until after his death. The opinion was divided on the meaning of Kubrick's detached view of this shocking future, but, whether the discord drew the curious or Kubrick's scathing diagnosis spoke to the chaotic cultural moment, A Clockwork Orange became a hit. On the heels of New York Film Critics Circle awards as Best Film, Best Director, and Best Screenplay, Kubrick received Oscar nominations in all three categories.

 

 

 

 

I was excited by everything about it: the plot, the ideas, the characters, and, of course, the language. The story functions, of course, on several levels: political, sociological, philosophical, and, what's most important, on a dreamlike psychological-symbolic level.

 

"

 

behind the novel

 

 

 

In 1959, the teacher of English and literature, Anthony Burgess, lost consciousness during his own lesson. After taking a picture of the head, the doctors discovered a brain tumor in him and predicted that in a year’s time Anthony would disappear into another world. He had written a little before, but only the diagnosis had pushed him to vigorous activity to raise money. One of the novels created in anticipation of the alleged death was the "Clockwork Orange." In 1943, Burgess' wife was raped by four soldiers in front of his eyes. It led to a miscarriage and a great family tragedy. It was the case the author thought about while writing his book. The main message of that work was, according to Anthony, "Christian free will and the power of forgiveness" (he was a very religious person).

screenplay

 

 

 

The cinematic adaptation of A Clockwork Orange (1962) was not initially planned. Screenplay writer Terry Southern gave Kubrick a copy of the novel, but, as he was developing a Napoleon Bonaparte–related project, Kubrick put it aside. Kubrick's wife, in an interview, stated she then gave him the novel after having read it. It had an immediate impact. Of his enthusiasm for it, Kubrick said:

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

He wrote a script faithful to the novel and the filming began in September 1970.

 

Kubrick wrote a screenplay faithful to the novel, saying, "I think whatever Burgess had to say about the story was said in the book, but I did invent a few useful narrative ideas and reshape some of the scenes." Kubrick based the script on the shortened US edition of the book, which omitted the final chapter.

Kubrick allegedly didn't like the book upon first reading because of the Nadsat language Burgess created for the novel. The language, literally translated as the Russian word for "teen" and comprised of Russian and Cockney rhyming slang, confused the eventual director.

 

McDowell is brilliant

 

 

 

The acting of Malcolm McDowell as Alex DeLarge, the main character, is really awesome. Some critics have even classified it as brilliant, and I think, it is for sure, the best role this actor has ever played. In fact, Kubrick said that if he couldn’t have McDowell playing the main role he probably would never have made the film.

Designer Milena Canonero sought to create a skewed near-future society with the costumes for A Clockwork Orange. But Kubrick and Canonero, had trouble pinning down the look of Alex's costume.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

When McDowell, a cricket fan, came in for a costume fitting with his gear—including protective cup—Kubrick told him to keep them out and incorporate his white shirt and cup into the costume. When McDowell started to dress by putting the jockstrap under his pants, Kubrick told him it'd look better over his pants instead, and the look made it into the final movie.

singing in the rain

 

 

 

The song Singing in the Rain was used by Malcolm McDowell during a scene when his character and his droogs break into a writer's house (Patrick Magee) and cause destruction before raping his wife (Adrienne Corri).

 

McDowell chose the cheery song by Gene Kelly from the classic musical because

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

it was the only one [song] I sorta half knew the words to.

"

Gene Kelly in Singing In The Rain (1952)

 

 

 

 

Kubrick paid $10,000 to use 30 seconds of the song. Later Kubrick invited Stanley Donen, the director of the musical classic, to view his scene and then asked Donen’s personal permission to use the song for the sequence. "He wanted to make sure I wasn’t offended," Donen reports in the biography Dancing on the Ceiling. "Why would I be? It didn’t affect the movie Singing in the Rain." Gene Kelly, who had performed the famous number in the 1952 film, felt otherwise. When Kelly and Kubrick met at an awards ceremony following Clockwork’s release, the danceman refused to talk to the director.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Malcolm McDowell, 1971

 

 

 

 

McDowell and Kubrick spent hours recording the film’s voiceovers in the two weeks following production. To break the routine, the pair would play ping pong on a table outside the recording studio. When McDowell learned that he would only be paid for a week of this work, Kubrick explained that a week had been spent playing ping pong.
